 # ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE
 
 Summaries for scanner-reported CVEs that Debian or upstream treat as non-actionable for stock OS packages in this image.
 
 ## CVE-2018-20796
 
 ## Overview: What Is CVE-2018-20796?
 
 CVE-2018-20796 is reported against GNU C Library (`glibc`) and concerns **uncontrolled recursion** in POSIX regular-expression matching (`regexec` / related code paths such as `check_dst_limits_calc_pos_1` in `posix/regexec.c`). Crafted patterns can drive deep recursion and **resource exhaustion** (denial of service via stack or CPU), not memory corruption in the usual exploit sense.
 
 **Glibc’s security policy explicitly excludes this class of issue from treatment as a security vulnerability**, and Debian’s tracker marks it **unimportant** with **no fixed version** aimed at “closing” the CVE.
 
 ---
 
 ## Debian tracker: “Not treated as vulnerability”
 
 On the [Debian security tracker](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2018-20796), **Notes** reference upstream discussion and state (in substance) that the issue is **not treated as a vulnerability**, with a link to **[glibc Security Exceptions](https://sourceware.org/glibc/wiki/Security%20Exceptions)**.
 
 Release rows may still show **vulnerable** for `glibc` while the **fixed version** column for unstable shows **(unfixed)** and urgency **unimportant** — meaning **no CVE-driven security update** is planned in the same way as for typical glibc flaws.
 
 ---
 
 ## Why Scanners Still Flag Trixie and Other Debian Releases
 
 Security scanners match:
 
 - Installed `glibc` source package and version
 - CVE metadata (e.g. CWE-674, availability impact)
 
 They often **do not** encode glibc’s **security exceptions** or Debian’s **unimportant** classification, so dashboards show a **HIGH**-style CVE even when **distributors and upstream reject it as a security boundary**.
 
 ---
 
 ## CVE-2018-20796 — glibc / regexp
 
 - **Component:** GNU C Library (`glibc`), POSIX regex / `regexec`
 - **Class of issue:** Resource exhaustion via crafted expression (policy: not a security bug per glibc wiki)
 - **Debian tracker:** Bullseye, Bookworm, **Trixie** (`glibc` e.g. `2.41-12+deb13u2`), sid/forky — listed **vulnerable**; **fixed version (unfixed)**; **unimportant**
 - **Related discussion:** Debian notes link [debbugs.gnu.org #34141](https://debbugs.gnu.org/cgi/bugreport.cgi?bug=34141) and [bug-gnulib thread](https://lists.gnu.org/archive/html/bug-gnulib/2019-01/msg00108.html)
 
 ### Illustrative tracker view
 
 | Release  | Package | High-level Debian posture     |
 |----------|---------|--------------------------------|
 | bullseye | glibc   | vulnerable row / unimportant |
 | bookworm | glibc   | vulnerable row / unimportant |
 | trixie   | glibc   | vulnerable row / unimportant |
 | sid      | glibc   | unfixed / unimportant        |
 
 There is **no separate “trixie security fix”** whose purpose is to satisfy this CVE as a supported remediation path.
 
 ---
 
 ## Why Rebuilding glibc in Containers Is the Wrong Default
 
 - Replacing distro `glibc` is fragile and breaks ABI expectations for the entire image
 - Upstream does not offer this as a **security fix** under their published policy
 - **Do not** feed untrusted regex to libc matchers; that is the operational control that matches vendor intent
 
 ---
 
 ## Audits: Wording vs. “False Positive”
 
 The CVE ID is still attached to real `glibc` packages, so many teams avoid calling it a strict **false positive**. Clear alternatives:
 
 - **Not a security vulnerability per glibc Security Exceptions and Debian (unimportant)**  
 - **Accepted risk / exception** with tracker and wiki citations
 
 **Recommendation:** Document CVE-2018-20796 as **non-actionable** for stock Debian **Trixie** images for security-remediation purposes, unless you have an unusual requirement to compile a private `glibc` (almost never justified for this CVE alone).
 
 ---
 
 ## Summary
 
 - CVE-2018-20796 is a **resource exhaustion / regexp** report; glibc policy: **not a security vulnerability**
 - Debian: **unimportant**, **(unfixed)** — no vendor patch story aligned with scanner “fix” expectations
 - **Trixie** is in the same posture as other current Debian releases in the tracker
 - Prefer **policy exception / not actionable** language over a bare **false positive** unless your glossary defines FP broadly
 
 ---
 
 ## References
 
 - [glibc wiki – Security Exceptions](https://sourceware.org/glibc/wiki/Security%20Exceptions)
 - [Debian Security Tracker – CVE-2018-20796](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2018-20796)
 - [NVD – CVE-2018-20796](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2018-20796)
 
 ## CVE-2019-1010022
 
 ## Overview: What Is CVE-2019-1010022?
 
 CVE-2019-1010022 is assigned against GNU C Library (`glibc`) and describes a claimed **mitigation bypass** involving NPTL and stack-guard behavior in hypothetical stack-overflow exploitation scenarios. Container scanners routinely match it to any image that ships `glibc`, including Debian stable and testing (`trixie`).
 
 **Upstream and Debian do not treat this as a security vulnerability that warrants a tracked corrective release in the usual sense.**
 
 ---
 
 ## Why Scanners Flag It Even When Distributions Do Not Act
 
 Security scanners (Trivy, Grype, Snyk, etc.) may report CVE-2019-1010022 because:
 
 - The CVE is linked to `glibc` versions present in the image
 - NVD text describes impact in abstract terms (“mitigation bypass”)
 - Debian’s security tracker can still list releases as **vulnerable** while marking urgency **unimportant** and **no fixed version**
 
 That combination is confusing for compliance dashboards but **does not imply an available vendor patch you should apply inside a random application image**.
 
 ---
 
 ## CVE-2019-1010022 — glibc / NPTL
 
 - **Component:** GNU C Library (`glibc`), NPTL
 - **Claimed issue:** Bypass of stack-guard mitigation when exploiting a stack buffer overflow
 - **Upstream status:** Treated as a **non-security bug**; **no real threat** (see Sourceware BZ #22850)
 - **Debian tracker:** Bullseye, Bookworm, Trixie, and sid entries show affected `glibc` versions; **fixed version** for unstable is **(unfixed)** with urgency **unimportant**
 
 ### Illustrative Debian tracker view
 
 | Release  | Package | Tracker note (high level)        |
 |----------|---------|----------------------------------|
 | bullseye | glibc   | listed vulnerable / unimportant  |
 | bookworm | glibc   | listed vulnerable / unimportant  |
 | trixie   | glibc   | listed vulnerable / unimportant  |
 | sid      | glibc   | unfixed / unimportant            |
 
 There is **no Debian security update** whose purpose is to “close” this CVE the way fixes exist for typical glibc CVEs.
 
 ---
 
 ## Why Rebuilding glibc in Containers Is the Wrong Default
 
 - Replacing distribution `glibc` breaks ABI and toolchain assumptions for the whole image
 - Debian does not provide a supported “hotfix” path for this issue as a security priority
 - Chasing this CVE in a custom base image usually yields **no meaningful risk reduction** aligned with vendor judgment
 
 ---
 
 ## How to Describe This in Audits (Not a Bare “False Positive”)
 
 Strictly speaking, many findings are **not** classic false positives: the CVE ID is attached to real `glibc` packages. Better wording:
 
 - **Disputed CVE / not a security issue per upstream and Debian (unimportant)**  
 - Or **accepted risk** with references below
 
 Reserve **false positive** for cases where the scanner is wrong about the **component, version, or applicability**. Here, **actionability** is what distributions reject—not necessarily the presence of `glibc` in the SBOM.
 
 **Recommendation:** Document CVE-2019-1010022 as **non-actionable** for stock Debian images unless your policy mandates a full unsupported glibc rebuild—which is almost never justified solely for this entry.
 
 ---
 
 ## Summary
 
 - CVE-2019-1010022 is disputed; upstream does not treat it as a security bug
 - Debian marks it **unimportant** with **no fixed glibc version** in the tracker sense used for this CVE
 - **Trixie** and other Debian releases do not ship a separate “fix package” aimed at satisfying this CVE as a security boundary
 - Prefer **disputed / risk accepted** language over **false positive** unless your internal glossary defines FP more broadly
 
 ---
 
 ## References
 
 - [Sourceware Bugzilla #22850](https://sourceware.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=22850)
 - [Debian Security Tracker – CVE-2019-1010022](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2019-1010022)
 - [NVD – CVE-2019-1010022](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2019-1010022)
 
 ## CVE-2019-1010023
 
 ## Overview: What Is CVE-2019-1010023?
 
 CVE-2019-1010023 is assigned against GNU Libc (`glibc`) and describes a scenario involving the **`ldd` helper** and the dynamic loader (**`libld` / `ld.so`**) when **`ldd` is run on untrusted ELF objects**. CVE text speaks of re-mapping loaded objects and worst-case code execution if a victim cooperates (e.g. runs `ldd` on attacker-supplied binaries).
 
 **Upstream explicitly treats this as a non-security bug and “no real threat”** in the same class of disputed glibc CVEs; Debian follows with **unimportant** and **no fixed version** in the tracker table for this CVE.
 
 ---
 
 ## Operational reality: `ldd` on untrusted files
 
 `ldd` works by invoking the dynamic linker on a program. **Running `ldd` (or executing untrusted ELFs) is already unsafe by design** if inputs are hostile. Hardening production systems means **not** pointing `ldd` at arbitrary binaries from untrusted parties—not rebuilding `glibc` solely to silence a CVE row.
 
 ---
 
 ## Debian security tracker (including Trixie)
 
 Per the [Debian tracker for CVE-2019-1010023](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2019-1010023):
 
 - **Package:** `glibc`
 - **Trixie (example):** `2.41-12+deb13u2` — row still shows **vulnerable**
 - **Fixed version (unstable):** **(unfixed)**
 - **Urgency:** **unimportant**
 - **Notes:** **Not treated as a security issue by upstream** → [Sourceware Bugzilla #22851](https://sourceware.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=22851)
 
 There is **no Debian security update** whose role is to “patch CVE-2019-1010023” the way normal glibc advisories work.
 
 ---
 
 ## Why scanners still flag stock Debian images
 
 Tools map **installed `glibc`** to CVE metadata. They generally **do not** encode:
 
 - That exploitation hinges on **social engineering / misuse** (`ldd` on malicious ELFs)
 - Upstream’s **non-security** classification
 - Debian’s **unimportant** + **(unfixed)** posture
 
 So compliance dashboards can show a critical-sounding CVE even when **distributors do not plan a CVE-specific fix**.
 
 ---
 
 ## CVE-2019-1010023 — glibc / `ldd` / loader
 
 - **Component:** `glibc` — `ldd` / dynamic linker (`libld` / `ld.so` interaction)
 - **Attack shape (CVE narrative):** User runs `ldd` on crafted ELF(s) supplied by an attacker
 - **Upstream:** Non-security bug; no real threat (BZ #22851)
 - **Debian:** Bullseye, Bookworm, **Trixie**, sid/forky — **vulnerable** rows; **(unfixed)**; **unimportant**
 
 ### Illustrative tracker view
 
 | Release  | Package | Debian posture (this CVE)      |
 |----------|---------|---------------------------------|
 | bullseye | glibc   | vulnerable row / unimportant   |
 | bookworm | glibc   | vulnerable row / unimportant   |
 | trixie   | glibc   | vulnerable row / unimportant   |
 | sid      | glibc   | (unfixed) / unimportant        |
 
 ---
 
 ## Why rebuilding `glibc` in containers is the wrong default
 
 - Fragile ABI impact for the entire image
 - **No vendor-supported “close this CVE” path** from Debian for this entry
 - Correct control is **policy**: never run `ldd` on untrusted binaries; treat untrusted ELFs like untrusted code
 
 ---
 
 ## Audits: wording vs. “false positive”
 
 The CVE is tied to real `glibc` packages, so strict **false positive** is often debatable. Prefer:
 
 - **Disputed / classified non-security by upstream; Debian unimportant**  
 - Or **accepted risk / exception** citing Sourceware #22851 and the Debian tracker
 
 **Recommendation:** Document CVE-2019-1010023 as **non-actionable** for typical server/container workloads that **do not** run `ldd` on untrusted artifacts.
 
 ---
 
 ## Summary
 
 - CVE-2019-1010023 centers on **`ldd` misuse** with untrusted ELF; upstream: **not a security issue**
 - Debian **Trixie** and other releases: **unimportant**, **(unfixed)** — no dedicated fix package to install for this CVE row
 - Mitigation is **operational**, not a custom `glibc` rebuild
 - Cite **Sourceware #22851** and the **Debian tracker** in exception registers
 
 ---
 
 ## References
 
 - [Sourceware Bugzilla #22851](https://sourceware.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=22851)
 - [Debian Security Tracker – CVE-2019-1010023](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2019-1010023)
 - [NVD – CVE-2019-1010023](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2019-1010023)
